# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: atmospheric-science
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:atmospheric-science/adam-dziewonski] Dziewonski was born in Lwów, which was then a part of Poland, currently a part of Ukraine.
[src:atmospheric-science/adam-dziewonski] After having earned a master's degree from the University of Warsaw, Poland (1960), and a Doctorate of Technical Sciences from the Academy of Mines and Metallurgy, Cracow, Poland (1965) Dziewonski taught at the University of Texas at Dallas for several years before settling at Harvard.
[src:atmospheric-science/adam-dziewonski] In the 1960s and 1970s, Dziewonski and his collaborators laid the foundation to understanding the underlying cause of tectonic plate motions by exploring convection currents in the Earth's mantle with radial maps of seismic property variations, based on measurements of seismic waves.
[src:atmospheric-science/adam-dziewonski] These studies led to the development of the Preliminary reference Earth model (PREM) in collaboration with Don Anderson; PREM established an accurate radial model of the Earth for seismic velocities, attenuation, and density.
[src:atmospheric-science/adam-dziewonski] Starting in the 1980s, Dziewonski led two original and powerful research efforts.
[src:atmospheric-science/adam-dziewonski] He extended the radial Earth models to be fully three-dimensional, along the way mapping and interpreting four "grand" structures.
[src:atmospheric-science/adam-dziewonski] The four include two regions of higher-than-average wavespeed, inferred to be cold and sinking mantle, one under the western edge of the Americas and the other under southern Eurasia.
[src:atmospheric-science/adam-dziewonski] The two other features are large-scale regions of slower-than-average wavespeed, inferred to be hot and rising superplumes, located at the bottom of the mantle under the middle of the Pacific Ocean and Africa.
[src:atmospheric-science/adam-dziewonski] His other research direction systematically determined the orientation and magnitude of the deformation for most of the significant earthquakes that have been well-recorded.
[src:atmospheric-science/adam-dziewonski] These results are known as the Harvard CMTs (centroid moment tensor solutions) and are continued today at Lamont–Doherty Earth Observatory by Göran Ekström and Meredith Nettles as the Global CMT Project.
[src:atmospheric-science/adam-dziewonski] In 1995 he was also elected a member of the United States National Academy of Sciences.
[src:atmospheric-science/adam-dziewonski] He died in Cambridge, Massachusetts, on March 1, 2016.
[src:atmospheric-science/aeronomy] "Aeronomy" later also began to refer to the study of the corresponding regions of the atmospheres of other planets.
[src:atmospheric-science/aeronomy] Aeronomy can be divided into three main branches: **terrestrial aeronomy**, **planetary aeronomy**, and **comparative aeronomy**.
[src:atmospheric-science/aeronomy] (center) are among the tools aeronomers use to gather data on the Earth's upper atmosphere.
[src:atmospheric-science/aeronomy] Terrestrial aeronomers study atmospheric tides and upper-atmospheric lightning discharges such as red sprites, sprite halos, blue jets, and ELVES.
[src:atmospheric-science/aeronomy] They also investigate the causes of dissociation and ionization processes in the Earth's upper atmosphere.
[src:atmospheric-science/aeronomy] Terrestrial aeronomers use ground-based telescopes, balloons, satellites, and sounding rockets to gather data from the upper atmosphere.
[src:atmospheric-science/aeronomy] Atmospheric tides are global-scale periodic oscillations of the Earth′s atmosphere, analogous in many ways to ocean tides.
[src:atmospheric-science/aeronomy] Atmospheric tides dominate the dynamics of the mesosphere and lower thermosphere, serving as an important mechanism for transporting energy from the upper atmosphere into the lower atmosphere.
[src:atmospheric-science/aeronomy] Terrestrial aeronomers study atmospheric tides because an understanding of them is essential to an understanding of the atmosphere as a whole and of benefit in improving the understanding of meteorology.
[src:atmospheric-science/aeronomy] Modeling and observations of atmospheric tides allow researchers to monitor and predict changes in the Earth's atmosphere.
[src:atmospheric-science/aeronomy] "Upper-atmospheric lightning" or "upper-atmospheric discharge" are terms aeronomers sometimes use to refer to a family of electrical-breakdown phenomena in the Earth's upper atmosphere that occur well above the altitudes of the tropospheric lightning observed in the lower atmosphere.
[src:atmospheric-science/aeronomy] Currently, the preferred term for an electrical-discharge phenomenon induced in the upper atmosphere by tropospheric lightning is "transient luminous event" (TLE).
[src:atmospheric-science/aeronomy] There are various types of TLEs including red sprites, sprite halos, blue jets, and ELVES (an acronym for "Emission of Light and Very-Low-Frequency perturbations due to Electromagnetic Pulse Sources").
[src:atmospheric-science/air-mass-thunderstorm] An **air-mass thunderstorm**, also called an "ordinary", "single cell", "isolated" or "garden variety" thunderstorm, is a thunderstorm that is generally weak and usually not severe.
[src:atmospheric-science/air-mass-thunderstorm] These storms form in environments where at least some amount of Convective Available Potential Energy (CAPE) is present, but with very low levels of wind shear and helicity.
[src:atmospheric-science/air-mass-thunderstorm] The lifting source, which is a crucial factor in thunderstorm development, is usually the result of uneven heating of the surface, though they can be induced by weather fronts and other low-level boundaries associated with wind convergence.
[src:atmospheric-science/air-mass-thunderstorm] The energy needed for these storms to form comes in the form of insolation, or solar radiation.
[src:atmospheric-science/air-mass-thunderstorm] Air-mass thunderstorms do not move quickly, last no longer than an hour, and have the threats of lightning, as well as showery light, moderate, or heavy rainfall.
[src:atmospheric-science/air-mass-thunderstorm] Lightning characteristics are related to characteristics of the parent thunderstorm, and could induce wildfires near thunderstorms with minimal rainfall.
[src:atmospheric-science/air-mass-thunderstorm] On unusual occasions, there could be a weak downburst and small hail.
[src:atmospheric-science/air-mass-thunderstorm] They are common in temperate zones during a summer afternoon.
[src:atmospheric-science/air-mass-thunderstorm] Like all thunderstorms, the mean-layered wind field the storms form within determine motion.
[src:atmospheric-science/air-mass-thunderstorm] When the deep-layered wind flow is light, outflow boundary progression will determine storm movement.
[src:atmospheric-science/air-mass-thunderstorm] Since thunderstorms can be a hazard to aviation, pilots are advised to fly above any haze layers within regions of better visibility and to avoid flying under the anvil of these thunderstorms, which can be regions where hail falls from the parent thunderstorm.
[src:atmospheric-science/air-mass-thunderstorm] Vertical wind shear is also a hazard near the base of thunderstorms which have generated outflow boundaries.
[src:atmospheric-science/air-mass-thunderstorm] The trigger for the lift of the initial cumulus cloud can be insolation heating the ground producing thermals, areas where two winds converge forcing air upwards, or where winds blow over terrain of increasing elevation.
[src:atmospheric-science/air-mass-thunderstorm] The moisture rapidly cools into liquid drops of water due to the cooler temperatures at high altitude, which appears as *cumulus* clouds.
[src:atmospheric-science/air-mass-thunderstorm] As the water vapor condenses into liquid, latent heat is released which warms the air, causing it to become less dense than the surrounding dry air.
[src:atmospheric-science/air-mass-thunderstorm] The air tends to rise in an *updraft* through the process of convection (hence the term convective precipitation).
[src:atmospheric-science/air-mass-thunderstorm] This creates a low-pressure zone beneath the forming thunderstorm, otherwise known as a cumulonimbus cloud.
[src:atmospheric-science/air-mass-thunderstorm] In a typical thunderstorm, approximately 5×108 kg of water vapor is lifted into the Earth's atmosphere.
[src:atmospheric-science/air-mass-thunderstorm] As they form in areas of minimal vertical wind shear, the thunderstorm's rainfall creates a moist and relatively cool outflow boundary which undercuts the storm's low level inflow, and quickly causes dissipation.
[src:atmospheric-science/air-mass-thunderstorm] Waterspouts, small hail, and strong wind gusts can occur in association with these thunderstorms.
[src:atmospheric-science/air-mass-thunderstorm] Also known as single cell thunderstorms, these are the typical summer thunderstorms in many temperate locales.
[src:atmospheric-science/air-mass-thunderstorm] They also occur in the cool unstable air which often follows the passage of a cold front from the sea during winter.
[src:atmospheric-science/air-mass-thunderstorm] Within a cluster of thunderstorms, the term "cell" refers to each separate principal updraft.
[src:atmospheric-science/air-mass-thunderstorm] Thunderstorm cells occasionally form in isolation, as the occurrence of one thunderstorm can develop an outflow boundary which sets up new thunderstorm development.
[src:atmospheric-science/air-mass-thunderstorm] Such storms are rarely severe and are a result of local atmospheric instability; hence the term "air mass thunderstorm".
[src:atmospheric-science/air-mass-thunderstorm] When such storms have a brief period of severe weather associated with them, it is known as a pulse severe storm.
[src:atmospheric-science/air-mass-thunderstorm] Pulse severe storms are poorly organized due to the minimal vertical wind shear in the storm's environment and occur randomly in time and space, making them difficult to forecast.
[src:atmospheric-science/air-mass-thunderstorm] Between formation and dissipation, single cell thunderstorms normally last 20–30 minutes.
[src:atmospheric-science/air-mass-thunderstorm] The two major ways thunderstorms move are via advection of the wind and propagation along outflow boundaries towards sources of greater heat and moisture.
[src:atmospheric-science/air-mass-thunderstorm] Many thunderstorms move with the mean wind speed through the Earth's troposphere, or the lowest 8 kilometres (5.0 mi) of the Earth's atmosphere.
[src:atmospheric-science/air-mass-thunderstorm] Younger thunderstorms are steered by winds closer to the Earth's surface than more mature thunderstorms as they tend not to be as tall.
[src:atmospheric-science/air-mass-thunderstorm] If the gust front, or leading edge of the outflow boundary, moves ahead of the thunderstorm, the thunderstorm's motion will move in tandem with the gust front.
[src:atmospheric-science/air-mass-thunderstorm] This is more of a factor with thunderstorms with heavy precipitation (HP), such as air-mass thunderstorms.
[src:atmospheric-science/air-mass-thunderstorm] When thunderstorms merge, which is most likely when numerous thunderstorms exist in proximity to each other, the motion of the stronger thunderstorm normally dictates future motion of the merged cell.
[src:atmospheric-science/air-mass-thunderstorm] The stronger the mean wind, the less likely other processes will be involved in storm motion.
[src:atmospheric-science/air-mass-thunderstorm] On weather radar, storms are tracked by using a prominent feature and tracking it from scan to scan.
[src:atmospheric-science/air-mass-thunderstorm] Convective rain, or showery precipitation, occurs from cumulonimbus clouds.
[src:atmospheric-science/air-mass-thunderstorm] It falls as showers with rapidly changing intensity.
[src:atmospheric-science/air-mass-thunderstorm] Convective precipitation falls over a certain area for a relatively short time, as convective clouds such as thunderstorms have limited horizontal extent.
[src:atmospheric-science/air-mass-thunderstorm] Most precipitation in the tropics appears to be convective.
[src:atmospheric-science/air-mass-thunderstorm] Graupel and hail are good indicators of convective precipitation and thunderstorms.
[src:atmospheric-science/air-mass-thunderstorm] In mid-latitudes, convective precipitation is intermittent and often associated with baroclinic boundaries such as cold fronts, squall lines, and warm fronts.
[src:atmospheric-science/air-mass-thunderstorm] High rainfall rates are associated with thunderstorms with larger raindrops and these leads to fading of microwave echoes, starting above the frequency of 10 gigahertz (GHz) but is more severe above frequencies of 15 GHz, which could lead to misinterpretation of radar intensity of the precipitation.
[src:atmospheric-science/air-mass-thunderstorm] Relationships between lightning frequency and the height of precipitation within thunderstorms have been found.
[src:atmospheric-science/air-mass-thunderstorm] Thunderstorms which show radar returns above 14 kilometres (8.7 mi) in height are associated with storms which have more than ten lightning flashes per minute.
[src:atmospheric-science/air-mass-thunderstorm] There is also a correlation between the total lightning rate and the size of the thunderstorm, its updraft velocity, and amount of graupel over land.
[src:atmospheric-science/air-mass-thunderstorm] The same relationships fail over tropical oceans, however.
[src:atmospheric-science/air-mass-thunderstorm] Lightning from low precipitation (LP) thunderstorms is one of the leading causes of wildfires.
[src:atmospheric-science/air-mass-thunderstorm] In areas where these thunderstorms form in isolation and horizontal visibility is good, pilots can evade these storms rather easily.
[src:atmospheric-science/air-mass-thunderstorm] In more moist atmospheres which become hazy, pilots navigate above the haze layer in order to get a better vantage point of these storms.
[src:atmospheric-science/air-mass-thunderstorm] Flying under the anvil of thunderstorms is not advised, as hail is more likely to fall in such areas outside the thunderstorm's main rain shaft.
[src:atmospheric-science/air-mass-thunderstorm] When an outflow boundary forms due to a shallow layer of rain-cooled air spreading out near ground level from the parent thunderstorm, both speed and directional wind shear can result at the leading edge of the three-dimensional boundary.
[src:atmospheric-science/air-mass-thunderstorm] The stronger the outflow boundary is, the stronger the resultant vertical wind shear will become.
[src:atmospheric-science/air-pollution] Outdoor air pollution comes from burning fossil fuels for electricity and transport, wildfires, some industrial processes, waste management, demolition and agriculture.
[src:atmospheric-science/air-pollution] Indoor air pollution is often from burning firewood or agricultural waste for cooking and heating.
[src:atmospheric-science/air-pollution] Other sources of air pollution include dust storms and volcanic eruptions.
[src:atmospheric-science/air-pollution] Many sources of local air pollution, especially burning fossil fuels, also release greenhouse gases that cause global warming.
[src:atmospheric-science/air-pollution] However, air pollution may limit warming locally.
[src:atmospheric-science/air-pollution] Air pollution kills 7 to 8 million people each year.
[src:atmospheric-science/air-pollution] It is a significant risk factor for a number of diseases, including stroke, heart disease, chronic obstructive pulmonary disease (COPD), asthma, coronavirus and lung cancer.
[src:atmospheric-science/air-pollution] Particulate matter is the most deadly, both for indoor and outdoor air pollution.
[src:atmospheric-science/air-pollution] Ozone affects crops, and forests are damaged by the pollution that causes acid rain.
[src:atmospheric-science/air-pollution] Overall, the World Bank has estimated that welfare losses (premature deaths) and productivity losses (lost labor) caused by air pollution cost the world economy over $8 trillion per year.
[src:atmospheric-science/air-pollution] Various technologies and strategies reduce air pollution.
[src:atmospheric-science/air-pollution] Key approaches include clean cookers, fire protection, improved waste management, dust control, industrial scrubbers, electric vehicles and renewable energy.
[src:atmospheric-science/air-pollution] National air quality laws have often been effective, notably the 1956 Clean Air Act in Britain and the 1963 US Clean Air Act.
[src:atmospheric-science/air-pollution] International efforts have had mixed results: the Montreal Protocol almost eliminated harmful ozone-depleting chemicals, while international action on climate change has been less successful.
[src:atmospheric-science/air] The **atmosphere of Earth** consists of a layer of mixed gas (commonly referred to as **air**) that is retained by gravity, surrounding the Earth's surface.
[src:atmospheric-science/air] It contains variable quantities of suspended aerosols and particulates that create weather features such as clouds and hazes.
[src:atmospheric-science/air] The atmosphere serves as a protective buffer between the Earth's surface and outer space.
[src:atmospheric-science/air] It shields the surface from most meteoroids and ultraviolet solar radiation, reduces diurnal temperature variation – the temperature extremes between day and night, and keeps it warm through heat retention via the greenhouse effect.
[src:atmospheric-science/air] The atmosphere redistributes heat and moisture among different regions via air currents, and provides the chemical and climate conditions that allow life to exist and evolve on Earth.
[src:atmospheric-science/air] By mole fraction (i.e., by quantity of molecules), dry air contains 78.08% nitrogen, 20.95% oxygen, 0.93% argon, 0.04% carbon dioxide, and small amounts of other trace gases (see Composition below for more detail).
[src:atmospheric-science/air] Air also contains a variable amount of water vapor, on average around 1% at sea level, and 0.4% over the entire atmosphere.
[src:atmospheric-science/air] Earth's primordial atmosphere consisted of gases accreted from the solar nebula, but the composition changed significantly over time, affected by many factors such as volcanism, outgassing, impact events, weathering and the evolution of life (particularly the photoautotrophs).
[src:atmospheric-science/air] In the present day, human activity has contributed to atmospheric changes, such as climate change (mainly through deforestation and fossil-fuel–related global warming), ozone depletion and acid deposition.
[src:atmospheric-science/air] The atmosphere has a mass of about 5.15×1018 kg, three quarters of which is within about 11 km (6.8 mi; 36,000 ft) of the surface.
[src:atmospheric-science/air] The atmosphere becomes thinner with increasing altitude, with no definite boundary between the atmosphere and outer space.
[src:atmospheric-science/air] The Kármán line at 100 km (62 mi) is often used as a conventional definition of the edge of space.
[src:atmospheric-science/air] Several layers can be distinguished in the atmosphere based on characteristics such as temperature and composition, namely the troposphere, stratosphere, mesosphere, thermosphere (formally the ionosphere), and exosphere.
[src:atmospheric-science/air] Air composition, temperature and atmospheric pressure vary with altitude.
[src:atmospheric-science/air] Air suitable for use in photosynthesis by terrestrial plants and respiration of terrestrial animals is found within the troposphere.
[src:atmospheric-science/air] The study of Earth's atmosphere and its processes is called atmospheric science (aerology), and includes multiple subfields, such as climatology and atmospheric physics.
[src:atmospheric-science/air] Early pioneers in the field include Léon Teisserenc de Bort and Richard Assmann.
[src:atmospheric-science/air] The study of the historic atmosphere is called paleoclimatology.
[src:atmospheric-science/air] The three major constituents of Earth's atmosphere are nitrogen, oxygen, and argon.
[src:atmospheric-science/air] Water vapor accounts for roughly 0.25% of the atmosphere by mass.
[src:atmospheric-science/air] The remaining gases are often referred to as trace gases, among which are other greenhouse gases, principally carbon dioxide, methane, nitrous oxide, and ozone.
[src:atmospheric-science/air] Besides argon, other noble gases, neon, helium, krypton, and xenon are also present.
[src:atmospheric-science/air] Filtered air includes trace amounts of many other chemical compounds.
[src:atmospheric-science/air] Many substances of natural origin may be present in locally and seasonally variable small amounts as aerosols in an unfiltered air sample, including dust of mineral and organic composition, pollen and spores, sea spray, and volcanic ash.
[src:atmospheric-science/air] Various industrial pollutants also may be present as gases or aerosols, such as chlorine (elemental or in compounds), fluorine compounds, and elemental mercury vapor.
[src:atmospheric-science/air] Sulfur compounds such as hydrogen sulfide and sulfur dioxide (SO2) may be derived from natural sources or from industrial air pollution.
[src:atmospheric-science/air] The average molecular weight of dry air, which can be used to calculate densities or to convert between mole fraction and mass fraction, is about 28.946 or 28.964 g/mol.
[src:atmospheric-science/air] This is decreased when the air is humid.
[src:atmospheric-science/air] Up to an altitude of around 100 km (62 mi), atmospheric turbulence mixes the component gases so that their relative concentrations remain the same.
[src:atmospheric-science/air] There exists a transition zone from roughly 80 to 120 km (50 to 75 mi) where this turbulent mixing gradually yields to molecular diffusion.
[src:atmospheric-science/air] The latter process forms the heterosphere where the relative concentration of lighter gases increase with altitude.
[src:atmospheric-science/air] In general, air pressure and density decrease with altitude in the atmosphere.
[src:atmospheric-science/air] However, temperature has a more complicated profile with altitude and may remain relatively constant or even increase with altitude in some regions (see the temperature section).
[src:atmospheric-science/air] Because the general pattern of the temperature/altitude profile, or lapse rate, is constant and measurable by means of instrumented balloon soundings, the temperature behavior provides a useful metric to distinguish atmospheric layers.
[src:atmospheric-science/air] The exosphere is the outermost layer of Earth's atmosphere (though it is so tenuous that some scientists consider it to be part of interplanetary space rather than part of the atmosphere).
[src:atmospheric-science/air] It extends from the thermopause (also known as the "exobase") at the top of the thermosphere to a poorly defined boundary with the solar wind and interplanetary medium.
[src:atmospheric-science/air] The altitude of the exobase varies from about 500 kilometres (310 mi; 1,600,000 ft) to about 1,000 kilometres (620 mi) in times of higher incoming solar radiation.
[src:atmospheric-science/air] The upper limit varies depending on the definition.
[src:atmospheric-science/air] Various authorities consider it to end at about 10,000 kilometres (6,200 mi) or about 190,000 kilometres (120,000 mi)—about halfway to the moon, where the influence of Earth's gravity is about the same as radiation pressure from sunlight.
[src:atmospheric-science/air] The geocorona visible in the far ultraviolet (caused by neutral hydrogen) extends to at least 100,000 kilometres (62,000 mi).
[src:atmospheric-science/air] This layer is mainly composed of extremely low densities of hydrogen, with limited amounts of helium, carbon dioxide, and nascent oxygen closer to the exobase.
[src:atmospheric-science/air] The atoms and molecules are so far apart that they can travel hundreds of kilometres without colliding with one another.
[src:atmospheric-science/air] Thus, the exosphere no longer behaves like a gas, and the particles constantly escape into space.
[src:atmospheric-science/air] These free-moving particles follow ballistic trajectories and may migrate in and out of the magnetosphere or the solar wind.
[src:atmospheric-science/air] Every second, the Earth loses about 3 kg of hydrogen, 50 g of helium, and much smaller amounts of other constituents.
[src:atmospheric-science/air] The exosphere is too far above Earth for meteorological phenomena to be possible.
[src:atmospheric-science/air] The exosphere contains many of the artificial satellites that orbit Earth.
[src:atmospheric-science/air] The thermosphere is the second-highest layer of Earth's atmosphere.
[src:atmospheric-science/air] It extends from the mesopause (which separates it from the mesosphere) at an altitude of about 80 km (50 mi) up to the thermopause at an altitude range of 500–1000 km (310–620 mi).
[src:atmospheric-science/air] The height of the thermopause varies considerably due to changes in solar activity.
[src:atmospheric-science/air] The passage of the dusk and dawn solar terminator creates background density perturbations up to a factor of two through this layer, forming a dominant feature in this region.
[src:atmospheric-science/air] Because the thermopause lies at the lower boundary of the exosphere, it is also referred to as the exobase.
[src:atmospheric-science/air] Overlapping the thermosphere, from 50 to 600 kilometres (31 to 373 mi) above Earth's surface, is the ionosphere – a region of enhanced plasma density.
[src:atmospheric-science/air] The temperature of the thermosphere gradually increases with height and can rise as high as 1500 °C (2700 °F), though the gas molecules are so far apart that its temperature in the usual sense is not very meaningful.
[src:atmospheric-science/air] This temperature increase is caused by absorption of ionizing UV and X-ray emission from the Sun.
[src:atmospheric-science/air] The air is so rarefied that an individual molecule (of oxygen, for example) travels an average of 1 kilometre (0.62 mi; 3300 ft) between collisions with other molecules.
[src:atmospheric-science/air] Although the thermosphere has a high proportion of molecules with high energy, it would not feel hot to a human in direct contact, because its density is too low to conduct a significant amount of energy to or from the skin.
[src:atmospheric-science/air] This layer is completely cloudless and free of water vapor.
[src:atmospheric-science/air] However, non-hydrometeorological phenomena such as the aurora borealis and aurora australis are occasionally seen in the thermosphere at an altitude of around 100 km (62 mi).
[src:atmospheric-science/air] The colors of the aurora are linked to the properties of the atmosphere at the altitude they occur.
[src:atmospheric-science/air] The most common is the green aurora, which comes from atomic oxygen in the 1S state, and occurs at altitudes from 120 to 400 km (75 to 250 mi).
[src:atmospheric-science/air] The International Space Station orbits in the thermosphere, between 370 and 460 km (230 and 290 mi).
[src:atmospheric-science/air] It is this layer where many of the satellites orbiting the Earth are present.
[src:atmospheric-science/air] The mesosphere is the third highest layer of Earth's atmosphere, occupying the region above the stratosphere and below the thermosphere.
[src:atmospheric-science/air] It extends from the stratopause at an altitude of about 50 km (31 mi) to the mesopause at 80–85 km (50–53 mi) above sea level.
[src:atmospheric-science/air] Temperatures drop with increasing altitude to the mesopause that marks the top of this middle layer of the atmosphere.
[src:atmospheric-science/air] It is the coldest place on Earth and has an average temperature around −85 °C (−120 °F; 190 K).
[src:atmospheric-science/air] Because the atmosphere absorbs sound waves at a rate that is proportional to the square of the frequency, audible sounds from the ground do not reach the mesosphere.
[src:atmospheric-science/air] Infrasonic waves can reach this altitude, but they are difficult to emit at a high power level.
[src:atmospheric-science/air] Just below the mesopause, the air is so cold that even the very scarce water vapor at this altitude can condense into polar-mesospheric noctilucent clouds of ice particles.
[src:atmospheric-science/air] These are the highest clouds in the atmosphere and may be visible to the naked eye if sunlight reflects off them about an hour or two after sunset or similarly before sunrise.
[src:atmospheric-science/air] They are most readily visible when the Sun is around 4 to 16 degrees below the horizon.
[src:atmospheric-science/air] Lightning-induced discharges known as transient luminous events (TLEs) occasionally form in the mesosphere above tropospheric thunderclouds.
[src:atmospheric-science/air] The mesosphere is also the layer where most meteors and satellites burn up upon atmospheric entrance.
[src:atmospheric-science/air] It is too high above Earth to be accessible to jet-powered aircraft and balloons, and too low to permit orbital spacecraft.
[src:atmospheric-science/air] The mesosphere is mainly accessed by sounding rockets and rocket-powered aircraft.
[src:atmospheric-science/air] The stratosphere is the second-lowest layer of Earth's atmosphere.
[src:atmospheric-science/air] It lies above the troposphere and is separated from it by the tropopause.
[src:atmospheric-science/air] This layer extends from the top of the troposphere at roughly 12 km (7.5 mi) above Earth's surface to the stratopause at an altitude of about 50 to 55 km (31 to 34 mi).
[src:atmospheric-science/air] 99% of the total mass of the atmosphere lies below 30 km (19 mi), and the atmospheric pressure at the top of the stratosphere is roughly 1/1000 the pressure at sea level.
[src:atmospheric-science/air] It contains the ozone layer, which is the part of Earth's atmosphere that contains relatively high concentrations of that gas.
[src:atmospheric-science/air] The stratosphere defines a layer in which temperatures rise with increasing altitude.
[src:atmospheric-science/air] This rise in temperature is caused by the absorption of ultraviolet radiation (UV) from the Sun by the ozone layer, which restricts turbulence and mixing.
[src:atmospheric-science/air] Although the temperature may be −80 °C (−110 °F; 190 K) at the tropopause, the top of the stratosphere is much warmer, and may be just below 0 °C.
[src:atmospheric-science/air] This layer is unique to the Earth; neither Mars nor Venus have a stratosphere because of low abundances of oxygen in their atmospheres.
[src:atmospheric-science/air] The stratospheric temperature profile creates very stable atmospheric conditions, so the stratosphere lacks the weather-producing air turbulence that is so prevalent in the troposphere.
[src:atmospheric-science/air] Consequently, the stratosphere is almost completely free of clouds and other forms of weather.
[src:atmospheric-science/air] However, polar stratospheric or nacreous clouds are occasionally seen in the lower part of this layer of the atmosphere where the air is coldest.
[src:atmospheric-science/air] The stratosphere is the highest layer that can be accessed by jet-powered aircraft.
[src:atmospheric-science/air] The troposphere is the lowest layer of Earth's atmosphere.
[src:atmospheric-science/air] It extends from Earth's surface to an average height of about 12 km (7.5 mi), although this altitude varies from about 9 km (5.6 mi) at the geographic poles to 17 km (11 mi) at the Equator, with some variation due to weather.
[src:atmospheric-science/air] The troposphere is bounded above by the tropopause, a boundary marked in most places by a temperature inversion (i.e. a layer of relatively warm air above a colder one), and in others by a zone that is isothermal with height.
[src:atmospheric-science/air] Although variations do occur, the temperature usually declines with increasing altitude in the troposphere because the troposphere is mostly heated through energy transfer from the surface.
[src:atmospheric-science/air] Thus, the lowest part of the troposphere (i.e.
[src:atmospheric-science/air] Earth's surface) is typically the warmest section of the troposphere.
[src:atmospheric-science/air] This promotes vertical mixing (hence, the origin of its name in the Greek word τρόπος, *tropos*, meaning "turn").
[src:atmospheric-science/air] The troposphere contains roughly 80% of the mass of Earth's atmosphere.
[src:atmospheric-science/air] The troposphere is denser than all its overlying layers because a larger atmospheric weight sits on top of the troposphere and causes it to be more severely compressed.
[src:atmospheric-science/air] Fifty percent of the total mass of the atmosphere is located in the lower 5.5 km (3.4 mi) of the troposphere.
[src:atmospheric-science/air] Nearly all atmospheric water vapor or moisture is found in the troposphere, so it is the layer where most of Earth's weather takes place.
[src:atmospheric-science/air] The ability of the atmosphere to retain water decreases as the temperature declines, so 90% of the water vapor is held in the lower part of the troposphere.
[src:atmospheric-science/air] It has basically all the weather-associated cloud genus types generated by active wind circulation, although very tall cumulonimbus thunder clouds can penetrate the tropopause from below and rise into the lower part of the stratosphere.
[src:atmospheric-science/air] Most conventional aviation activity takes place in the troposphere, and it is the only layer accessible by propeller-driven aircraft.
[src:atmospheric-science/air] Contrails are formed from jet engine water emission at altitudes where the atmospheric temperature is about −53 °C (−63 °F); typically around 7.7 km (4.8 mi) for modern engines.
[src:atmospheric-science/air] Above this altitude lies the heterosphere, which includes the exosphere and most of the thermosphere.
[src:atmospheric-science/air] Here, the chemical composition varies with altitude.
[src:atmospheric-science/air] is large compared with the size of motions that cause mixing.
[src:atmospheric-science/air] with the heavier ones, such as oxygen and nitrogen, present only near the bottom of the heterosphere.
[src:atmospheric-science/air] The upper part of the heterosphere is composed almost completely of hydrogen, the lightest element.
[src:atmospheric-science/air] The average temperature of the atmosphere at Earth's surface is 14 °C (57 °F; 287 K) or 15 °C (59 °F; 288 K), depending on the reference.
[src:atmospheric-science/air] The average atmospheric pressure at sea level is defined by the International Standard Atmosphere as 101325 pascals (760.00 Torr; 14.6959 psi; 760.00 mmHg).
[src:atmospheric-science/air] This is sometimes referred to as a unit of standard atmospheres (atm).
[src:atmospheric-science/air] Total atmospheric mass is 5.1480×1018 kg (1.13494×1019 lb), about 2.5% less than would be inferred from the average sea-level pressure and Earth's area of 51007.2 megahectares, this portion being displaced by Earth's mountainous terrain.
[src:atmospheric-science/air] Atmospheric pressure is the total weight of the air above unit area at the point where the pressure is measured.
[src:atmospheric-science/air] Thus air pressure varies with location and weather.
[src:atmospheric-science/air] Air pressure decreases exponentially with altitude at a rate that depends on the air temperature.
[src:atmospheric-science/air] The rate of decrease is determined by a temperature-dependent parameter called the scale height: for each increase in altitude by this height, the pressure decreases by a factor of *e* (the base of natural logarithms, approximately 2.718).
[src:atmospheric-science/air] For Earth, this value is typically 5.5 to 6 km for altitudes up to around 80 km (50 mi).
[src:atmospheric-science/air] However, the atmosphere is more accurately modeled with a customized equation for each layer that takes gradients of temperature, molecular composition, solar radiation and gravity into account.
[src:atmospheric-science/air] At heights over 100 km, the atmosphere is not well mixed, so each chemical species has its own scale height.
[src:atmospheric-science/air] At altitudes of 200 to 300 km, the combined scale height is 20 to 30 km.
[src:atmospheric-science/air] Even above the Kármán line, significant atmospheric effects such as auroras still occur.
[src:atmospheric-science/air] Meteors begin to glow in this region, though the larger ones may not burn up until they penetrate more deeply.
[src:atmospheric-science/air] The various layers of Earth's ionosphere, important to HF radio propagation, begin below 100 km and extend beyond 500 km.
[src:atmospheric-science/air] By comparison, the International Space Station typically orbit at 370–460 km, within the F-layer of the ionosphere, where they encounter enough atmospheric drag to require reboosts every few months, otherwise orbital decay will occur, resulting in a return to Earth.
[src:atmospheric-science/air] Depending on solar activity, satellites can experience noticeable atmospheric drag at altitudes as high as 600–800 km.
[src:atmospheric-science/air] Starting at sea level, the temperature decreases with altitude until reaching the stratosphere at around 11 km.
[src:atmospheric-science/air] Above, the temperature stabilizes over a large vertical distance.
[src:atmospheric-science/air] Starting above about 20 km, the temperature increases with height, due to heating within the ozone layer caused by the capture of significant ultraviolet radiation from the Sun by the molecular oxygen and ozone gas in this region.
[src:atmospheric-science/air] A second region of increasing temperature with altitude occurs at very high altitudes, in the aptly-named thermosphere above 90 km.
[src:atmospheric-science/air] During the night, the ground radiates more energy than it gains from the atmosphere.
[src:atmospheric-science/air] As energy is conducted from the nearby atmosphere to the cooler ground, it creates a temperature inversion where the local temperature increases with altitude up to around 1,000 m.
[src:atmospheric-science/air] For example, at sea level the speed of sound is 340 m/s.
[src:atmospheric-science/air] At the average temperature of the stratosphere, −60 °C, the speed of sound decreases to 290 m/s.
[src:atmospheric-science/air] Density is not measured directly but is calculated from measurements of temperature, pressure and humidity using the equation of state for air (a form of the ideal gas law).
[src:atmospheric-science/air] Atmospheric density decreases as the altitude increases.
[src:atmospheric-science/air] This variation can be approximately modeled using the barometric formula.
[src:atmospheric-science/air] More sophisticated models are used to predict the orbital decay of satellites.
[src:atmospheric-science/air] The average mass of the atmosphere is about 5 quadrillion (5×1015) tonnes or 1/1,200,000 the mass of Earth.
[src:atmospheric-science/air] According to the American National Center for Atmospheric Research, "The total mean mass of the atmosphere is 5.1480×1018 kg with an annual range due to water vapor of 1.2 or 1.5×1015 kg, depending on whether surface pressure or water vapor data are used; somewhat smaller than the previous estimate.
[src:atmospheric-science/air] Solar radiation (or sunlight) is the energy Earth receives from the Sun.
[src:atmospheric-science/air] Earth also emits radiation back into space, but at longer wavelengths that humans cannot see.
[src:atmospheric-science/air] As energy propagates through the atmosphere, it is impacted by the process of radiative transfer.
[src:atmospheric-science/air] That is, some of the incoming and emitted radiation is subject to absorption, emission, and scattering by the atmosphere.
[src:atmospheric-science/air] Another portion of the incident energy is reflected, with the two most important atmospheric reflectors being dust and clouds.
[src:atmospheric-science/air] Depending on the properties of the aerosol, clouds can reflect up to 70% of the incident radiation.
[src:atmospheric-science/air] Globally, clouds reflect 20% of the incoming energy, contributing two thirds of the planet's total albedo.
[src:atmospheric-science/air] In May 2017, glints of light, seen as twinkling from an orbiting satellite a million miles away, were found to be reflected light from ice crystals in the troposphere.
[src:atmospheric-science/air] When light passes through Earth's atmosphere, photons interact with it through *scattering*.
[src:atmospheric-science/air] If the light does not interact with the atmosphere, it is called *direct radiation* and is what you see if you were to look directly at the Sun.
[src:atmospheric-science/air] *Indirect radiation* is light that has been scattered in the atmosphere.
[src:atmospheric-science/air] For example, on an overcast day when you cannot see your shadow, there is no direct radiation reaching you, it has all been scattered.
[src:atmospheric-science/air] As another example, due to a phenomenon called Rayleigh scattering, shorter (blue) wavelengths scatter more easily than longer (red) wavelengths.
[src:atmospheric-science/air] This is why the sky looks blue; you are seeing scattered blue light.
[src:atmospheric-science/air] Because the Sun is close to the horizon, the Sun's rays pass through more atmosphere than normal before reaching your eye.
[src:atmospheric-science/air] Much of the blue light has been scattered out, leaving the red light in a sunset.
[src:atmospheric-science/air] Different molecules absorb different wavelengths of radiation.
[src:atmospheric-science/air] For example, O2 and O3 absorb almost all radiation with wavelengths shorter than 300 nanometres.
[src:atmospheric-science/air] Water (H2O) absorbs at many wavelengths above 700 nm.
[src:atmospheric-science/air] When a molecule absorbs a photon, it increases the energy of the molecule.
[src:atmospheric-science/air] This heats the atmosphere, but the atmosphere also cools by emitting radiation, as discussed below.
[src:atmospheric-science/air] In astronomical spectroscopy, the absorption of specific frequencies by the atmosphere is referred to as telluric contamination.
[src:atmospheric-science/air] The combined absorption spectra of the gases in the atmosphere leave "windows" of low opacity, allowing the transmission of only certain bands of light.
[src:atmospheric-science/air] The optical window runs from around 300 nm (ultraviolet-C) up into the range humans can see, the visible spectrum (commonly called light), at roughly 400–700 nm and continues to the infrared to around 1100 nm.
[src:atmospheric-science/air] There are also infrared and radio windows that transmit some infrared and radio waves at longer wavelengths.
[src:atmospheric-science/air] For example, the radio window runs from about one centimetre to about eleven-metre waves.
[src:atmospheric-science/air] Because of its temperature, the atmosphere emits infrared radiation.
[src:atmospheric-science/air] For example, on clear nights Earth's surface cools down faster than on cloudy nights.
[src:atmospheric-science/air] This is because clouds (H2O) are strong absorbers and emitters of infrared radiation.
[src:atmospheric-science/air] This is also why it becomes colder at night at higher elevations.
[src:atmospheric-science/air] The greenhouse effect is directly related to this absorption and emission effect.
[src:atmospheric-science/air] Some gases in the atmosphere absorb and emit infrared radiation, but do not interact in this manner with sunlight in the visible spectrum.
[src:atmospheric-science/air] Common examples of these are CO2 and H2O.
[src:atmospheric-science/air] Without greenhouse gases in the atmosphere, the average temperature of Earth's surface would be a frozen −18 °C (0 °F), rather than the present comfortable average of 15 °C (59 °F).
[src:atmospheric-science/air] The refractive index of air is close to, but just greater than, 1.
[src:atmospheric-science/air] Systematic variations in the refractive index can lead to the bending of light rays over long optical paths.
[src:atmospheric-science/air] One example is that, under some circumstances, observers on board ships can see other vessels just over the horizon because light is refracted in the same direction as the curvature of Earth's surface.
[src:atmospheric-science/air] The refractive index of air depends on temperature, giving rise to refraction effects when the temperature gradient is large.
[src:atmospheric-science/air] An example of such effects is the mirage.
[src:atmospheric-science/air] The flow of air around the planet is divided into three main convection cells by latitude.
[src:atmospheric-science/air] Around the equator, the Hadley cell is driven by the rising flow of air along the equator.
[src:atmospheric-science/air] In the upper atmosphere, this air flows toward the poles.
[src:atmospheric-science/air] At mid latitudes, this circulation is reversed, with ground air flowing toward the poles with the Ferrel cell.
[src:atmospheric-science/air] Finally, in the high latitudes is the Polar cell, where air again rises and flows toward the poles.
[src:atmospheric-science/air] The interface between these cells is responsible for jet streams.
[src:atmospheric-science/air] These are narrow, fast moving bands that flow from west to east and typically form at an elevation of around 9,100 m (30,000 ft).
[src:atmospheric-science/air] Jet streams can shift around depending on conditions.
[src:atmospheric-science/air] They are strongest in winter, when the boundaries between hot and cold air are the most pronounced.
[src:atmospheric-science/air] In the middle latitudes, it is instabilities in the jet streams that are responsible for moving weather systems.
[src:atmospheric-science/air] As with the oceans, the Earth's atmosphere is subject to waves and tidal forces.
[src:atmospheric-science/air] These are triggered by non-uniform heating by the Sun, and by the daily solar cycle, respectively.
[src:atmospheric-science/air] Wave-like behavior can occur on a variety of scales, from smaller gravity waves that transfer momentum into the higher atmospheric layers, to much larger planetary waves, or Rossby waves.
[src:atmospheric-science/air] Atmospheric tides are periodic oscillations of the troposphere and stratosphere that transport energy to the upper atmosphere.
[src:atmospheric-science/air] The first atmosphere, during the Early Earth's Hadean eon, consisted of gases in the solar nebula, primarily hydrogen, and probably simple hydrides such as those now found in the gas giants (Jupiter and Saturn), notably water vapor, methane and ammonia.
[src:atmospheric-science/air] During this earliest era, the Moon-forming collision and numerous impacts with large meteorites heated the atmosphere, driving off the most volatile gases.
[src:atmospheric-science/air] The collision with Theia, in particular, melted and ejected large portions of Earth's mantle and crust and outgassed significant amounts of steam which eventually cooled and condensed to contribute to ocean water at the end of the Hadean.
[src:atmospheric-science/air] The increasing solidification of Earth's crust at the end of the Hadean closed off most of the advective heat transfer to the surface, causing the atmosphere to cool, which condensed most of the water vapor out of the air precipitating into a superocean.
[src:atmospheric-science/air] Further outgassing from volcanism, supplemented by gases introduced by huge asteroids during the Late Heavy Bombardment, created the subsequent Archean atmosphere, which consisted largely of nitrogen plus carbon dioxide, methane and inert gases.
[src:atmospheric-science/air] A major part of carbon dioxide emissions dissolved in water and reacted with metals such as calcium and magnesium during weathering of crustal rocks to form carbonates that were deposited as sediments.
[src:atmospheric-science/air] Water-related sediments have been found that date from as early as 3.8 billion years ago.
[src:atmospheric-science/air] About 3.4 billion years ago, nitrogen formed the major component of the then-stable "second atmosphere".
[src:atmospheric-science/air] The influence of the evolution of life has to be taken into account rather soon in the history of the atmosphere because hints of earliest life forms appeared as early as 3.5 billion years ago.
[src:atmospheric-science/air] How Earth at that time maintained a climate warm enough for liquid water and life, if the early Sun put out 30% lower solar radiance than today, is a puzzle known as the "faint young Sun paradox".
[src:atmospheric-science/air] The geological record however shows a continuous relatively warm surface during the complete early temperature record of Earth – with the exception of one cold glacial phase about 2.4 billion years ago.
[src:atmospheric-science/air] In the late Neoarchean, an oxygen-containing atmosphere began to develop, apparently due to a billion years of cyanobacterial photosynthesis (known as the Great Oxygenation Event), which have been found as stromatolite fossils from 2.7 billion years ago.
[src:atmospheric-science/air] The early basic carbon isotopy (isotope ratio proportions) strongly suggests conditions similar to the current, and that the fundamental features of the carbon cycle became established as early as 4 billion years ago.
[src:atmospheric-science/air] Ancient sediments in the Gabon dating from between about 2.15 and 2.08 billion years ago provide a record of Earth's dynamic oxygenation evolution.
[src:atmospheric-science/air] These fluctuations in oxygenation were likely driven by the Lomagundi-Jatuli Carbon Isotope Excursion.
[src:atmospheric-science/air] The constant re-arrangement of continents by plate tectonics influences the long-term evolution of the atmosphere by transferring carbon dioxide to and from large continental carbonate stores.
[src:atmospheric-science/air] Before this time, any oxygen produced by cyanobacterial photosynthesis would be readily removed by the oxidation of reducing substances on the Earth's surface, notably ferrous iron, sulfur and atmospheric methane.
[src:atmospheric-science/air] Free oxygen molecules did not start to accumulate in the atmosphere until the rate of production of oxygen began to exceed the availability of reductant materials that removed oxygen.
[src:atmospheric-science/air] This point signifies a shift from a reducing atmosphere to an oxidizing atmosphere.
[src:atmospheric-science/air] O2 showed major variations during the Proterozoic, including a billion-year period of euxinia, until reaching a steady state of more than 15% by the end of the Precambrian.
[src:atmospheric-science/air] The amount of oxygen in the atmosphere has fluctuated over the last 600 million years, reaching a peak of about 35% around 280 million years ago during the Carboniferous period, significantly higher than today's 21%.
[src:atmospheric-science/air] Two main processes govern changes in the atmosphere: the evolution of plants and their increasing role in carbon fixation, and the consumption of oxygen by rapidly diversifying animal faunae and also by plants for photorespiration and their own metabolic needs at night.
[src:atmospheric-science/air] Breakdown of pyrite and volcanic eruptions release sulfur into the atmosphere, which reacts and hence reduces oxygen in the atmosphere.
[src:atmospheric-science/air] However, volcanic eruptions also release carbon dioxide, which can fuel oxygenic photosynthesis by terrestrial and aquatic plants.
[src:atmospheric-science/air] The cause of the variation of the amount of oxygen in the atmosphere is not precisely understood.
[src:atmospheric-science/air] Periods with more oxygen in the atmosphere were often associated with more rapid development of animals.
[src:atmospheric-science/air] Since 1750, human activity, especially after the Industrial Revolution, has increased the concentrations of various greenhouse gases, most importantly carbon dioxide, methane and nitrous oxide.
[src:atmospheric-science/air] Greenhouse gas emissions, coupled with deforestation and destruction of wetlands via logging and land developments, have caused an observed rise in global temperatures, with the global average surface temperatures being 1.1 °C higher in the 2011–2020 decade than they were in 1850.
[src:atmospheric-science/air] It has raised concerns of man-made climate change, which can have significant environmental impacts such as sea level rise, ocean acidification, glacial retreat (which threatens water security), increasing extreme weather events and wildfires, ecological collapse and mass dying of wildlife.
[src:atmospheric-science/akatsuki-spacecraft] By using five different cameras working at several wavelengths,*Akatsuki* studied the stratification of the atmosphere, atmospheric dynamics, and cloud physics.
[src:atmospheric-science/akatsuki-spacecraft] Astronomers working on the mission reported detecting a possible gravity wave (not to be confused with gravitational waves) in Venus's atmosphere in December 2015.
[src:atmospheric-science/akatsuki-spacecraft] JAXA lost contact with the probe in late April 2024.
[src:atmospheric-science/akatsuki-spacecraft] Operation was terminated officially on 18 September 2025.
[src:atmospheric-science/akatsuki-spacecraft] Observations included cloud and surface imaging from an orbit around the planet with cameras operating in the infrared, visible and UV wavelengths to investigate the complex Venusian meteorology and elucidate the processes behind the mysterious atmospheric super-rotation.
[src:atmospheric-science/akatsuki-spacecraft] On Venus, while the planet rotates at 6 kilometres per hour (3.7 mph) at the equator, the atmosphere spins around the planet at 300 kilometres per hour (190 mph).
[src:atmospheric-science/akatsuki-spacecraft] Other experiments were designed to confirm the presence of lightning and to determine whether volcanism occurs currently on Venus.
[src:atmospheric-science/akatsuki-spacecraft] The solar arrays provided over 700 W of power while in Venus orbit.
[src:atmospheric-science/akatsuki-spacecraft] The total mass of the spacecraft at launch was 517.6 kg (1,141 lb).
[src:atmospheric-science/akatsuki-spacecraft] The mass of the science payload was 34 kg (75 lb).
[src:atmospheric-science/akatsuki-spacecraft] Propulsion was provided by a 500-newton (110 lbf) bi-propellant, hydrazine-dinitrogen tetroxide orbital maneuvering engine and twelve mono-propellant hydrazine reaction control thrusters, eight with 23 N (5.2 lbf) of thrust and four with 3 N (0.67 lbf).
[src:atmospheric-science/akatsuki-spacecraft] It was the first spacecraft to use a ceramic (silicon nitride) retrofire thruster.
[src:atmospheric-science/akatsuki-spacecraft] The total propellant mass at launch was 196.3 kg (433 lb).
[src:atmospheric-science/akatsuki-spacecraft] Communication was handled via an 8 GHz, 20-watt X-band transponder using the 1.6 m (5 ft 3 in) high-gain antenna.
[src:atmospheric-science/akatsuki-spacecraft] The high-gain antenna was flat to prevent heat from building up in it.
[src:atmospheric-science/akatsuki-spacecraft] *Akatsuki* also had a pair of medium-gain horn antennas mounted on turntables and two low-gain antennas for command uplink.
[src:atmospheric-science/akatsuki-spacecraft] The medium-gain horn antennas were used for housekeeping data downlink when the high-gain antenna was not facing Earth.
[src:atmospheric-science/akatsuki-spacecraft] The scientific payload consisted of six instruments.
[src:atmospheric-science/akatsuki-spacecraft] 4. the infrared 1 μm camera (**IR1**) imaged the night side heat radiation (0.90–1.01 μm) emitted from Venus's surface and help researchers to search for active volcanoes.
[src:atmospheric-science/akatsuki-spacecraft] While on the day side, it sensed the solar near-infrared radiation (0.90 μm) reflected by the middle clouds.
[src:atmospheric-science/akatsuki-spacecraft] Operation of the instrument was terminated in December 2016 due to an electronic failure.
[src:atmospheric-science/akatsuki-spacecraft] 5. the infrared 2 μm camera (**IR2**) studied the night side lower clouds' opacity to the thermal emission from the surface and deeper atmosphere (1.74–2.32 μm).
[src:atmospheric-science/akatsuki-spacecraft] It also sensed on the day side the CO2 band at 2.02 μm, which can be used to infer the altitude of the top of the clouds.
[src:atmospheric-science/akatsuki-spacecraft] Finally, the 1.65-μm filter was used during the cruise phase to study the zodiacal light.
[src:atmospheric-science/akatsuki-spacecraft] 6. the Ultra-Stable Oscillator (**USO**) for performing radio occultation experiments.
[src:atmospheric-science/akatsuki-spacecraft] A public relations campaign was held between October 2009 and January 2010 by the Planetary Society and JAXA, to allow individuals to send their name and a message aboard *Akatsuki*.
[src:atmospheric-science/akatsuki-spacecraft] Names and messages were printed in fine letters on an aluminium plate and placed aboard *Akatsuki*.
[src:atmospheric-science/akatsuki-spacecraft] 260,214 people submitted names and messages for the mission.
[src:atmospheric-science/akatsuki-spacecraft] Around 90 aluminium plates were created for the spacecraft, including three aluminium plates in which the images of the Vocaloid Hatsune Miku and her super deformed-styled figure Hachune Miku were printed.
[src:atmospheric-science/akatsuki-spacecraft] The spacecraft was launched on 20 May 2010 at 21:58:22 (UTC) from the Tanegashima Space Center, after being delayed because of weather from its initial 18 May scheduled target.
[src:atmospheric-science/akatsuki-spacecraft] The orbit insertion maneuver was confirmed to have started on time, but after the expected blackout due to occultation by Venus, the communication with the probe did not recover as planned.
[src:atmospheric-science/akatsuki-spacecraft] The probe was found to be in safe-hold mode, spin-stabilized state with ten minutes per rotation.
[src:atmospheric-science/akatsuki-spacecraft] Due to the low communication speed through the low-gain antenna, it took a while to determine the state of the probe.
[src:atmospheric-science/akatsuki-spacecraft] JAXA stated on 8 December that the probe's orbital insertion maneuver had failed.
[src:atmospheric-science/akatsuki-spacecraft] At a press conference on 10 December, officials reported that *Akatsuki*'s engines fired for less than three minutes, far less than what was required to enter into Venus orbit.
[src:atmospheric-science/akatsuki-spacecraft] Further research found that the likely reason for the engine malfunction was salt deposits jamming the valve between the helium pressurization tank and the fuel tank.
[src:atmospheric-science/akatsuki-spacecraft] As a result, engine combustion became oxidizer-rich, with resulting high combustion temperatures damaging the combustion chamber throat and nozzle.
[src:atmospheric-science/akatsuki-spacecraft] A similar vapor leakage problem caused the failure of NASA's *Mars Observer* probe in 1993.
[src:atmospheric-science/akatsuki-spacecraft] As a result, the probe was in a heliocentric orbit, rather than Venus orbit.
[src:atmospheric-science/akatsuki-spacecraft] Since the resulting orbit had an orbital period of 203 days, shorter than Venus's orbital period of 225 days, the probe drifted around the Sun compared to Venus.
[src:atmospheric-science/akatsuki-spacecraft] JAXA developed plans to attempt another orbital insertion burn when the probe returned to Venus in December 2015.
[src:atmospheric-science/akatsuki-spacecraft] This required placing the probe into "hibernation" or safe mode to prolong its life beyond the original 4.5-year design.
[src:atmospheric-science/akatsuki-spacecraft] JAXA expressed some confidence in keeping the probe operational, pointing to reduced battery wear, since the probe was then orbiting the Sun instead of its intended Venusian orbit.
[src:atmospheric-science/akatsuki-spacecraft] Telemetry data from the original failure suggested that the throat of its main engine, the orbit maneuver engine (OME) was still largely intact, and trial jet thrusts of the probe's onboard OME were performed twice, on 7 and 14 September 2011.
[src:atmospheric-science/akatsuki-spacecraft] However, the thrust was only about 40 newtons (9.0 lbf), which was 10% of expectations.
[src:atmospheric-science/akatsuki-spacecraft] Following these tests, it was determined that insufficient specific impulse would be available for orbital maneuvering by the OME.
[src:atmospheric-science/akatsuki-spacecraft] It was concluded that the remaining combustion chamber throat was completely destroyed by transient ignition of the engine.
[src:atmospheric-science/akatsuki-spacecraft] As a result, the selected strategy was to use four hydrazine attitude control thrusters, also called reaction control system (RCS), to drive the probe into orbit around Venus.
[src:atmospheric-science/akatsuki-spacecraft] Because the RCS thrusters do not need oxidiser, the remaining 65 kilograms (143 lb) of oxidiser (MON) was vented overboard in October 2011 to reduce the mass of the spacecraft.
[src:atmospheric-science/akatsuki-spacecraft] Three peri-Venus orbital maneuvers were executed on 1 November, 10 and 21 November 2011 using the RCS thrusters.
[src:atmospheric-science/akatsuki-spacecraft] A total delta-*v* of 243.8 metres per second (800 ft/s) was imparted to the spacecraft.
[src:atmospheric-science/akatsuki-spacecraft] Because the RCS thrusters' specific impulse is low compared to the specific impulse of the OME, the previously planned insertion into low Venusian orbit became impossible.
[src:atmospheric-science/akatsuki-spacecraft] Instead, the new plan was to place the probe in a highly elliptical orbit with an apoapsis of a hundred thousand kilometers and a periapsis of a few thousand kilometers from Venus.
[src:atmospheric-science/akatsuki-spacecraft] Engineers planned for the alternate orbit to be prograde (in the direction of the atmospheric super-rotation) and lie in the orbital plane of Venus.
[src:atmospheric-science/akatsuki-spacecraft] The method and orbit were announced by JAXA in February 2015, with an orbit insertion date of 7 December 2015.
[src:atmospheric-science/akatsuki-spacecraft] The probe reached its most distant point from Venus on 3 October 2013 and had been approaching the planet since then.
[src:atmospheric-science/akatsuki-spacecraft] Instead of taking about 30 hours to complete an orbit around Venus—as was originally planned—the new orbit targeted would place *Akatsuki* in a nine-day orbit after an adjustment in March 2016.
[src:atmospheric-science/akatsuki-spacecraft] A follow-up thruster burn on 26 March 2016 lowered *Akatsuki'*s apoapsis to about 370,000 km (230,000 mi), periapsis altitude periodically changing from 1,000 to 10,000 kilometres (620 to 6,210 mi), and shortened its orbital period from 13 to about 10 days.
[src:atmospheric-science/akatsuki-spacecraft] The orbiter started its two-year period of "regular" science operations in mid-May 2016.
[src:atmospheric-science/akatsuki-spacecraft] On 9 December 2016, the near-infrared 1-μm and 2-μm cameras became unavailable for observations due to an electronic failure.
[src:atmospheric-science/akatsuki-spacecraft] Its long-wave infrared camera, ultraviolet imager, and lightning and airglow camera continued normal operation.
[src:atmospheric-science/akatsuki-spacecraft] By April 2018, *Akatsuki* finished its regular observation phase, and entered an extended operation phase.
[src:atmospheric-science/akatsuki-spacecraft] Extended operations were approved until the end of 2020, with further mission extensions to be considered based on the spacecraft's condition at that time.
[src:atmospheric-science/akatsuki-spacecraft] As of November 2019, it was estimated that *Akatsuki* had enough fuel to continue operating for at least 2 more years.
[src:atmospheric-science/akatsuki-spacecraft] As of March 2024, operation was planned to continue through FY2028.
[src:atmospheric-science/akatsuki-spacecraft] In April 2024, degraded precision of attitude control resulted in failure of communication.
[src:atmospheric-science/akatsuki-spacecraft] JAXA declared the spacecraft's loss of contact with Earth on May 29, 2024.
[src:atmospheric-science/akatsuki-spacecraft] Three hours after insertion in December 2015 and in "a few glimmers in April and May" 2016 the craft's instruments recorded a "bow-shape feature in the atmosphere stretching 6,000 miles, almost pole to pole — a sideways smile".
[src:atmospheric-science/akatsuki-spacecraft] Scientists on the project termed the feature a "gravity wave" in the planet's winds above the Aphrodite Terra region of rift valleys and mountains reaching heights of over 4,000 metres (13,000 ft).
[src:atmospheric-science/akatsuki-spacecraft] The mission is collecting data in all relevant spectral bands from ultraviolet (280 nm) to mid-infrared wavelengths (10 μm).
[src:atmospheric-science/akatsuki-spacecraft] Images from the *Akatsuki* orbiter revealed something similar to jet stream winds in the low and middle cloud region, which extends from 45 to 60 kilometres (28 to 37 mi) in altitude.
[src:atmospheric-science/akatsuki-spacecraft] The wind speed maximized near the equator.
[src:atmospheric-science/akatsuki-spacecraft] In September 2017, JAXA scientists named this phenomenon 'Venusian equatorial jet'.
[src:atmospheric-science/akatsuki-spacecraft] They also published results on equatorial winds at the cloud-top level by tracking clouds on the UV spectrum.
[src:atmospheric-science/akatsuki-spacecraft] A significant result in 2018 is the appearance of thick clouds of small particles near the transition between upper and middle clouds, what was described as a "new and puzzling morphology of the complex cloud cover." By 2017, the science team published 3D maps on the Venus atmosphere structure.
[src:atmospheric-science/akatsuki-spacecraft] The physical quantities retrieved include the pressure, the temperature, the H 2SO 4 vapor density, and the ionospheric electron density and their variations.
[src:atmospheric-science/akatsuki-spacecraft] By the year 2019, the first results about the morphology, temporal changes and the winds at the middle clouds of Venus were published and merited the cover in *Geophysical Research Letters*, reporting unexpectedly high contrasts that might indicate the presence of absorbers like water.
[src:atmospheric-science/akatsuki-spacecraft] To image lightning, the orbiter had sight of the dark side of Venus for about 30 minutes every 10 days.
[src:atmospheric-science/akatsuki-spacecraft] In March 2020 a flash was detected and was determined unlikely to be a bolide or cosmic ray, however it was not confirmed to be lightning.
[src:atmospheric-science/atmospheric-science] Experimental instruments used in atmospheric science include satellites, rocketsondes, radiosondes, weather balloons, radars, and lasers.
[src:atmospheric-science/atmospheric-science] The term **aerology** (from Greek ἀήρ, *aēr*, "air"; and -λογία, *-logia*) is sometimes used as an alternative term for the study of Earth's atmosphere; in other definitions, aerology is restricted to the free atmosphere, the region above the planetary boundary layer.
[src:atmospheric-science/atmospheric-science] Atmospheric chemistry is a branch of atmospheric science in which the chemistry of the Earth's atmosphere and that of other planets is studied.
[src:atmospheric-science/atmospheric-science] It is a multidisciplinary field of research and draws on environmental chemistry, physics, meteorology, computer modeling, oceanography, geology and volcanology and other disciplines.
[src:atmospheric-science/atmospheric-science] Research is increasingly connected with other areas of study such as climatology.
[src:atmospheric-science/atmospheric-science] The composition and chemistry of the atmosphere is of importance for several reasons, but primarily because of the interactions between the atmosphere and living organisms.
[src:atmospheric-science/atmospheric-science] The composition of the Earth's atmosphere has been changed by human activity and some of these changes are harmful to human health, crops and ecosystems.
[src:atmospheric-science/atmospheric-science] Examples of problems which have been addressed by atmospheric chemistry include acid rain, photochemical smog and global warming.
[src:atmospheric-science/atmospheric-science] Atmospheric chemistry seeks to understand the causes of these problems, and by obtaining a theoretical understanding of them, allow possible solutions to be tested and the effects of changes in government policy evaluated.
[src:atmospheric-science/atmospheric-science] Atmospheric chemistry plays a major role in understanding the concentration of gases in our atmosphere that contribute to climate change.
[src:atmospheric-science/atmospheric-science] More specifically, when combined with atmospheric physics and biogeochemistry, it is useful in terms of studying the influence of greenhouse gases like CO2, N2O, and CH4, on Earth's radiative balance.
[src:atmospheric-science/atmospheric-science] According to UNEP, CO2 emissions increased to a new record of 57.1 GtCO2e, up 1.3% from the previous year.
[src:atmospheric-science/atmospheric-science] Previous GHG emissions growth from 2010-2019 averaged only +0.8% yearly, illustrating the dramatic increase in global emissions.
[src:atmospheric-science/atmospheric-science] The Global Nitrous Oxide Budget cited that atmospheric N2O has increased by roughly 25% between 1750 and 2022, having the fasted annual growth rate in 2020 and 2021.
[src:atmospheric-science/atmospheric-science] Atmospheric chemistry is critical in understanding what contributes to our changing climate.
[src:atmospheric-science/atmospheric-science] The warming of our climate is caused when CO2 emissions, constrained by biogeochemistry, are above a 0% increase.
[src:atmospheric-science/atmospheric-science] In order to stop temperatures from rising, there must be no CO2 emissions.
[src:atmospheric-science/atmospheric-science] By understanding the chemical composition and emission rates in our atmosphere alongside economic factors, researchers are able to trace back emissions back to their sources.
[src:atmospheric-science/atmospheric-science] About 26% of the 2023 GtCO2e was used for power, 15% for transportation, 11% in industry, 11% in agriculture, etc.
[src:atmospheric-science/atmospheric-science] In order to successfully reverse the human-driven damage contributing to global climate change, cuts of nearly 42% are needed by 2030 and are to be implementing using government intervention.
[src:atmospheric-science/atmospheric-science] This is one example of how atmospheric chemistry goes hand-in-hand with social and political policy, biogeochemistry, and economic factors.
[src:atmospheric-science/atmospheric-science] Atmospheric dynamics is the study of motion systems of meteorological importance, integrating observations at multiple locations and times and theories.
[src:atmospheric-science/atmospheric-science] Common topics studied include diverse phenomena such as thunderstorms, tornadoes, gravity waves, tropical cyclones, extratropical cyclones, jet streams, and global-scale circulations.
[src:atmospheric-science/atmospheric-science] The goal of dynamical studies is to explain the observed circulations on the basis of fundamental principles from physics.
[src:atmospheric-science/atmospheric-science] Atmospheric physics is the application of physics to the study of the atmosphere.
[src:atmospheric-science/atmospheric-science] Atmospheric physicists attempt to model Earth's atmosphere and the atmospheres of the other planets using fluid flow equations, chemical models, radiation balancing, and energy transfer processes in the atmosphere and underlying oceans and land.
[src:atmospheric-science/atmospheric-science] In order to model weather systems, atmospheric physicists employ elements of scattering theory, wave propagation models, cloud physics, statistical mechanics and spatial statistics, each of which incorporate high levels of mathematics and physics.
[src:atmospheric-science/atmospheric-science] Atmospheric physics has close links to meteorology and climatology and also covers the design and construction of instruments for studying the atmosphere and the interpretation of the data they provide, including remote sensing instruments.
[src:atmospheric-science/atmospheric-science] In the United Kingdom, atmospheric studies are underpinned by the Meteorological Office.
[src:atmospheric-science/atmospheric-science] National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration (NOAA) oversee research projects and weather modeling involving atmospheric physics.
[src:atmospheric-science/atmospheric-science] National Astronomy and Ionosphere Center also carries out studies of the high atmosphere.
[src:atmospheric-science/atmospheric-science] The Earth's magnetic field and the solar wind interact with the atmosphere, creating the ionosphere, Van Allen radiation belts, telluric currents, and radiant energy.
[src:atmospheric-science/atmospheric-science] Recent studies in atmospheric physics often rely on satellite-based observation.
[src:atmospheric-science/atmospheric-science] One example includes CALIPSO, or the Cloud-Aerosol Lidar and Infrared Pathfinder Satellite Observation.
[src:atmospheric-science/atmospheric-science] The CALIPSO mission, engineered by NASA and the Centre National d'Etudes Spatiales/CNES, studies how clouds and airborne particles play a role in regulating the weather, climate, and quality of Earth's atmosphere.
[src:atmospheric-science/atmospheric-science] Climatology is a science that derives knowledge and practices from the more specialized disciplines of meteorology, oceanography, geology, biology, and astronomy to study climate.
[src:atmospheric-science/atmospheric-science] In contrast to meteorology, which studies short-term weather systems lasting up to a few weeks, climatology studies the frequency and trends of those systems.
[src:atmospheric-science/atmospheric-science] It studies the periodicity of weather events over timescales ranging from years to millennia, as well as changes in long-term average weather patterns.
[src:atmospheric-science/atmospheric-science] Climatologists, those who practice climatology, study both the nature of climates – local, regional or global – and the natural or human-induced factors that cause climate variability and current ongoing global warming.
[src:atmospheric-science/atmospheric-science] Additionally, the occurrence of past climates on Earth, such as those arising from glacial periods and interglacials, can be used to predict future changes in climate.
[src:atmospheric-science/atmospheric-science] Oftentimes, climatology is studied in conjunction with another specialized discipline.
[src:atmospheric-science/atmospheric-science] ENSO describes a recurring climate pattern in which the temperature of waters in the central and eastern tropical Pacific Ocean changes periodically.
[src:atmospheric-science/atmospheric-science] AMOC is best described by NOAA as "a system of ocean currents that circulates water within the Atlantic Ocean, bringing warm water north and cold water south".
[src:atmospheric-science/atmospheric-science] This research has revealed that the collapse of the AMOC appears to be occurring sooner than when earlier models had predicted.
[src:atmospheric-science/atmospheric-science] It also expands on the fact that our economic and social systems are more vulnerable to El Nino impacts than previously thought.
[src:atmospheric-science/atmospheric-science] The study of climatology is vital in understanding current climate risks.
[src:atmospheric-science/atmospheric-science] Research is necessary to mitigate and monitor the efforts put forth towards are ever-evolving climate.
[src:atmospheric-science/atmospheric-science] Strengthening our knowledge within the realm of climatology allows us to better prepare for the impacts of extreme El Nino events, such as amplified droughts, floods, and heat extremes.
[src:atmospheric-science/atmospheric-science] Related disciplines include astrophysics, atmospheric physics, chemistry, ecology, physical geography, geology, geophysics, glaciology, hydrology, oceanography, and volcanology.
[src:atmospheric-science/atmospheric-science] Aeronomy is the scientific study of the upper atmosphere of the Earth — the atmospheric layers above the stratopause — and corresponding regions of the atmospheres of other planets, where the entire atmosphere may correspond to the Earth's upper atmosphere or a portion of it.
[src:atmospheric-science/atmospheric-science] A branch of both atmospheric chemistry and atmospheric physics, aeronomy contrasts with meteorology, which focuses on the layers of the atmosphere below the stratopause.
[src:atmospheric-science/atmospheric-science] In atmospheric regions studied by aeronomers, chemical dissociation and ionization are important phenomena.
[src:atmospheric-science/atmospheric-science] All of the Solar System's planets have atmospheres.
[src:atmospheric-science/atmospheric-science] This is because their gravity is strong enough to keep gaseous particles close to the surface.
[src:atmospheric-science/atmospheric-science] Larger gas giants are massive enough to keep large amounts of the light gases hydrogen and helium close by, while the smaller planets lose these gases into space.
[src:atmospheric-science/atmospheric-science] The composition of the Earth's atmosphere is different from the other planets because the various life processes that have transpired on the planet have introduced free molecular oxygen.
[src:atmospheric-science/atmospheric-science] Much of Mercury's atmosphere has been blasted away by the solar wind.
[src:atmospheric-science/atmospheric-science] The only moon that has retained a dense atmosphere is Titan.
[src:atmospheric-science/atmospheric-science] There is a thin atmosphere on Triton, and a trace of an atmosphere on the Moon.
[src:atmospheric-science/atmospheric-science] At least one extrasolar planet, HD 189733 b, has been claimed to possess such a weather system, similar to the Great Red Spot but twice as large.
[src:atmospheric-science/atmospheric-science] Hot Jupiters have been shown to be losing their atmospheres into space due to stellar radiation, much like the tails of comets.
[src:atmospheric-science/logy] Philology is an exception: while its meaning is closer to the first sense, the etymology of the word is similar to the second sense.
[src:atmospheric-science/logy] In English names for fields of study, the suffix *-logy* is most frequently found preceded by the euphonic connective vowel *o* so that the word ends in *-ology*.
[src:atmospheric-science/logy] In these Greek words, the root is always a noun and *-o-* is the combining vowel for all declensions of Greek nouns.
[src:atmospheric-science/logy] Linguists sometimes jokingly refer to haplology as *haplogy* (subjecting the word *haplology* to the process of haplology itself).
[src:atmospheric-science/logy] Per metonymy, words ending in *-logy* are sometimes used to describe a subject rather than the study of it (e.g., *technology*).
[src:atmospheric-science/logy] This usage is particularly widespread in medicine; for example, *pathology* is often used simply to refer to "the disease" itself (e.g., "We haven't found the pathology yet") rather than "the study of a disease".
[src:atmospheric-science/logy] Books, journals, and treatises about a subject also often bear the name of this subject (e.g., the scientific journal *Ecology*).
[src:atmospheric-science/logy] When appended to other English words, the suffix can also be used humorously to create nonce words (e.g., *beerology* as "the study of beer").
[src:atmospheric-science/logy] As with other classical compounds, adding the suffix to an initial word-stem derived from Greek or Latin may be used to lend grandeur or the impression of scientific rigor to humble pursuits, as in *cosmetology* ("the study of beauty treatment") or *cynology* ("the study of dog training").
[src:atmospheric-science/logy] The -logy or -ology suffix is commonly used to indicate finite series of art works like books or movies.
[src:atmospheric-science/logy] For paintings, the "tych" suffix is more common (e.g. diptych, triptych).
[src:atmospheric-science/logy] Further terms like duology (two, mostly in genre fiction) quadrilogy (four) and octalogy (eight) have been coined but are rarely used: for a series of 10, sometimes "decalog" is used (e.g. in the Virgin Decalog) instead of "decalogy".
